[{"id":42876,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"For refraction at a single spherical surface, we use the formula: $\\frac{\\mu_2}{v} - \\frac{\\mu_1}{u} = \\frac{\\mu_2 - \\mu_1}{R}$<br>Given data:<br>Refractive index of air $\\mu_1 = 1.0$<br>Refractive index of glass $\\mu_2 = 1.5$<br>Radius of curvature $R = +50$ cm (convex surface)<br>Object is at infinity for a parallel beam, so $u = -\\infty$<br>Substituting the values:<br>$\\frac{1.5}{v} - \\frac{1.0}{-\\infty} = \\frac{1.5 - 1.0}{50}$<br>$\\frac{1.5}{v} - 0 = \\frac{0.5}{50}$<br>$\\frac{1.5}{v} = \\frac{1}{100}$<br>$v = 1.5 \\times 100 = 150$ cm<br>The image is formed at a distance of $150$ cm from the pole (vertex) of the spherical surface.<br>The question asks for the distance $x$ from the centre of curvature.<br>Distance from centre of curvature $x = |v - R|$<br>$x = 150 - 50 = 100$ cm","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (22 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42904,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5L9gzDtxNqLAEbw69lMB8_2vpZAAIT9LtoxRb9Ni3M8.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7eL5gOubVl-hwkpKM-rUER8x6ZRZH22wQCiqA6kR2ok.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/njJbQvSbSqhYLhBWdlFKg9NcR7ieh0M3Xj4ruXrpzlM.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/l2PDBjUjKljwkuUfpnJ-Cal6NXVFjRt4N7cUtdo7MP4.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>"],"answer":2,"solution":"$(u+f)(v-f)=f^2$\n\n\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Jx9A3h9sk7KWGyiltecVu0lQTOuHewnaKvgm4L8g1Ho.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42864,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"Using the lensmaker's equation, in air:<br>$\\frac{1}{f_{air}} = (n - 1)\\left(\\frac{1}{R_1} - \\frac{1}{R_2}\\right)$ where $(n-1) = 0.5$ for glass with $n = 1.5$.<br>In water:<br>$\\frac{1}{f_{water}} = \\left(\\frac{n}{n_{water}} - 1\\right)\\left(\\frac{1}{R_1} - \\frac{1}{R_2}\\right)$ <br>$= \\left(\\frac{1.5}{4/3} - 1\\right)\\left(\\frac{1}{R_1} - \\frac{1}{R_2}\\right)$ <br>$= \\frac{1}{8}\\left(\\frac{1}{R_1} - \\frac{1}{R_2}\\right)$<br>Since $\\left(\\frac{1}{R_1} - \\frac{1}{R_2}\\right) = \\frac{2}{f_{air}} = \\frac{2}{18}$,<br>We get $\\frac{1}{f_{water}} = \\frac{1}{8} \\cdot \\frac{2}{18} = \\frac{1}{72}$, so $f_{water} = 72$ cm.<br>The difference is $f_{water} - f_{air} = 72 - 18 = 54$ cm.<br>Therefore $\\alpha = \\frac{54}{18} = 3$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (28 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43140,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{n} < \\frac{1}{2}$","$\\mathrm{n}>\\sqrt{2}$","$n>\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}$","$\\mathrm{n} < \\sqrt{2}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"Angle of incidence $\\mathrm{i}>\\mathrm{C}$ for total internal reflection. Here $\\mathrm{i}=45^{\\circ}$ inside the medium.\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& \\therefore 45^{\\circ}>\\sin ^{-1}(1 / n) \\\\\n& \\Rightarrow n>\\sqrt{ } 2 .\n\\end{aligned}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":42872,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["$\\cos ^{-1}\\left(\\frac{8}{9}\\right)$","$\\sin ^{-1}\\left(\\frac{9}{8}\\right)$","$\\cot ^{-1}\\left(\\frac{3}{\\sqrt{13}}\\right)$","$\\tan ^{-1}\\left(\\frac{8}{\\sqrt{17}}\\right)$"],"answer":3,"solution":"The refractive index of a medium is inversely proportional to the speed of light in that medium, given by $n = \\frac{c}{v}$.<br>For light travelling from medium $A$ to medium $B$, the critical angle $\\theta_c$ is defined when light travels from a denser to a rarer medium.<br>Given speeds are $v_A = 2.4 \\times 10^8$ m/s and $v_B = 2.7 \\times 10^8$ m/s.<br>The refractive indices are $n_A = \\frac{c}{v_A}$ and $n_B = \\frac{c}{v_B}$.<br>The critical angle $\\theta_c$ is given by $\\sin \\theta_c = \\frac{n_B}{n_A} = \\frac{v_A}{v_B}$.<br>Substituting the values: $\\sin \\theta_c = \\frac{2.4 \\times 10^8}{2.7 \\times 10^8} = \\frac{24}{27} = \\frac{8}{9}$.<br>To find the value in terms of $\\tan^{-1}$, we use the trigonometric identity for a right-angled triangle where perpendicular $p = 8$ and hypotenuse $h = 9$.<br>The base $b = \\sqrt{h^2 - p^2} = \\sqrt{9^2 - 8^2} = \\sqrt{81 - 64} = \\sqrt{17}$.<br>Thus, $\\tan \\theta_c = \\frac{p}{b} = \\frac{8}{\\sqrt{17}}$.<br>Therefore, $\\theta_c = \\tan^{-1}\\left(\\frac{8}{\\sqrt{17}}\\right)$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (23 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42925,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are true","Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Statement I is true but Statement II is false","Statement I is false but Statement II is true"],"answer":2,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} & \\frac{1}{\\mathrm{v}}-\\frac{1}{\\mathrm{u}}=\\frac{1}{\\mathrm{f}} \\\\ & \\frac{1}{\\mathrm{v}}-\\frac{1}{-2 \\mathrm{f}}=\\frac{1}{-\\mathrm{f}} \\\\ & \\Rightarrow \\frac{1}{\\mathrm{v}}=\\frac{-1}{2 \\mathrm{f}} \\Rightarrow \\mathrm{v}=-2 \\mathrm{f} \\\\ & \\frac{1}{\\mathrm{v}}=\\frac{1}{\\mathrm{u}}+\\frac{1}{\\mathrm{f}} \\Rightarrow \\text { Virtual image of Real object. }\\end{aligned}$\nIn statement II, it is not mentioned that object is real or virtual hence Statement II is false.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (09 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42978,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>732</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>333</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>414</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>732</mn></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a73d57f8-045c-4725-beeb-ec54d9da6ddb-image.png\" style=\"width: 249px; height: 130px;\" /></p><p>Given here,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>45</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math></p><p>Deviation in light ray,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>D</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>i</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>r</mi></math>, here,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi></math>&nbsp;is refracted ray.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>15</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>45</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>30</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math></p><p>Using Snell&#39;s law,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mi>sin</mi><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>sin</mi><mi>r</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>1</mn><mi>sin</mi><mn>45</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>&#956;</mi><mi>sin</mi><mn>30</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>&#956;</mi><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></p><p>Thus, the&nbsp;refractive index of the medium is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#956;</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>414</mn></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42995,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e37e9fd2-826e-44e9-9e46-c66a3644d7f2-image.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 129px;\" /></p><p>For the refraction at the left surface,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>u</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>&#8734;</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>R</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>+</mo><mn>15</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math>.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>v</mi></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mi>u</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow><mi>R</mi></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mo>&#8734;</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>+</mo><mn>15</mn></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>45</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p>For the refraction at the right&nbsp;surface,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>u</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>45</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>30</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>15</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>R</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>15</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>v</mi></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mi>u</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow><mi>R</mi></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow><mn>15</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>15</mn></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p>Therefore, the distance from the centre where the beam will converge is,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>15</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>22</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>225</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43066,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["<math><mn>1.60</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","<math><mn>0.16</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","<math><mn>0.32</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&nbsp;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","<math><mn>0.24</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">u</mi></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">u</mi></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.4</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math><br />From mirror formula,<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">u</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">u</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">u</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.4</mo></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>5</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">u</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.4</mo></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">u</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>5</mn></mfrac><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.4</mo></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.32</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math><br />So, distance of object from mirror<math><mo>=</mo><mn>0.32</mn><mi>&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42975,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["Scattering","Chromatic aberration&nbsp;","Spherical aberration","Polarisation"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4fcc95e7-e826-4411-9b31-fd3cfaa0ba49-6c7c808d-959b-408b-979b-0cf2274318f1-image(1).png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 172px;\" /></p><p>Due to difference in refractive index of a material for different wavelengths, the focal length will be different for different colours. This will cause a separation of parallel beam of white light. This phenomenon is known as chromatic aberration.</p><p>Polarisation&nbsp;is a property applying to transverse waves that specify the geometrical orientation of the oscillations.</p><p>When energy waves (such as light, sound, and various electromagnetic waves) are caused to depart from a straight path due to imperfections in the medium it is called Scattering.</p><p>Spherical aberration is present when the outer parts of a lens do not bring light rays into the same focus as the central part.&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (24 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42858,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"Sunlight comes from infinity and is focused at the principal focus of the convex lens. The paper burns in the shortest time when the intensity of light is maximum, which occurs at the focal point.<br><br>Therefore, the focal length of the convex lens is $f = 30$ cm.<br><br>Assuming the lens is equiconvex, the radii of curvature are $R_1 = 60$ cm and $R_2 = -60$ cm.<br><br>Using the Lens Maker's formula:<br><br>$\\dfrac{1}{f} = (\\mu - 1) \\left( \\dfrac{1}{R_1} - \\dfrac{1}{R_2} \\right)$<br><br>Substituting the given values:<br><br>$\\dfrac{1}{30} = (\\mu - 1) \\left( \\dfrac{1}{60} - \\left( -\\dfrac{1}{60} \\right) \\right)$<br><br>$\\dfrac{1}{30} = (\\mu - 1) \\left( \\dfrac{2}{60} \\right)$<br><br>$\\dfrac{1}{30} = (\\mu - 1) \\left( \\dfrac{1}{30} \\right)$<br><br>$\\mu - 1 = 1 \\Rightarrow \\mu = 2$<br><br>Given that the refractive index is $\\dfrac{\\alpha}{10}$:<br><br>$\\dfrac{\\alpha}{10} = 2 \\Rightarrow \\alpha = 20$<br><br>Answer: $20$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (02 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42945,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>For minimum deviation in a prism,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#956;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>sin</mi><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>D</mi><mrow><mi>m</mi><mi>i</mi><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>+</mo><mi>A</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>sin</mi><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mi>A</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mstyle></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>The value of minimum deviation is</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>sin</mi><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>D</mi><mrow><mi>m</mi><mi>i</mi><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>60</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>sin</mi><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mn>30</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></mstyle></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>sin</mi><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>D</mi><mrow><mi>m</mi><mi>i</mi><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>60</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mfenced><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>45</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>D</mi><mrow><mi>m</mi><mi>i</mi><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>60</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mfenced><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>D</mi><mrow><mi>m</mi><mi>i</mi><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>30</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (15 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43056,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["<math><mn>22</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"></mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","<math><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"></mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","<math><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"></mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","<math><mn>33</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"></mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<math><mi>M</mi><mo>.</mo><mi>P</mi><mo>.</mo><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub><mi></mi></mrow></mfrac><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>D</mi></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>e</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>;</mo><mn>375</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>150</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfrac><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>25</mn></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>e</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math><br /><math><mfrac><mrow><mn>375</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>30</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>25</mn></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>e</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><math><mfrac><mrow><mn>345</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>30</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>25</mn></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>e</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><math><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>e</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>750</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>345</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>2.17</mn><mi>c</mi><mi>m</mi><mo>;</mo><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>e</mi></mrow></msub><mo>≈</mo><mn>22</mn><mi>m</mi><mi>m</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (07 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43092,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["Two","Four","Three","Five"],"answer":2,"solution":"Reading one <math><mo>⇒</mo></math> without slab<br /><br />Reading two <math><mo>⇒</mo></math> with slab<br /><br />Reading three <math><mo>⇒</mo></math> with Lycopodium powder","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2016 (10 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":42960,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>85</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>70</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>51</mn></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The formula for a lens is given by&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>f</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>v</mi></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>u</mi></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>i</mi><mo>)</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>u</mi><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>100</mn><mo>&#177;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>80</mn><mo>&#177;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>20</mn><mo>&#177;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>180</mn><mo>&#177;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>100</mn><mo>&#177;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>80</mn><mo>&#177;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p>Substituting the&nbsp;values in the equation of focal length,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>f</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>v</mi></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>u</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>80</mn></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>20</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>5</mn><mn>80</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>f</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>16</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p>Differentiating the equation (i)</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>f</mi></mrow><msup><mi>f</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>v</mi></mrow><msup><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>u</mi></mrow><msup><mi>u</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></math>(Only positive sign is considered for&nbsp;error calculation)</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow><mn>6400</mn></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow><mn>400</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>17</mn><mn>6400</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>d</mi><mi>f</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>17</mn><mn>6400</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>16</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>272</mn></math></p><p>The percentage error is&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>f</mi></mrow><mi>f</mi></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>272</mn></mrow><mn>16</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>70</mn><mo>%</mo></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (06 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":43048,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["Inverted, real and magnified","Erect, virtual and magnified","Erect, virutual and unmagnified","Inverted, real and unmagnified"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>The image will form between&nbsp;the focus and centre&nbsp;of&nbsp;the concave mirror when we keep the object between the&nbsp;centre and infinity.It will be real image.&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/955e21b1-2176-49e1-abdc-b62d9ebb2dc5-image.png\" style=\"width: 312px; height: 236px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (02 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42873,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["between the focus $(F)$ and the centre of curvature $(C)$ of the mirror ONLY","between the pole($P$) and the focus $(F)$ of the concave mirror ONLY","beyond the centre of the curvature $(C)$ of the mirror ONLY","at any point beyond the focus $(F)$ of the mirror"],"answer":3,"solution":"In the parallax method for determining the focal length of a concave mirror, we use an object pin and its real image formed by the mirror.<br>The method of 'no parallax' involves aligning the tip of the object pin with the tip of its real image. This is only possible if the image formed is real.<br>For a concave mirror, a real image is formed only when the object is placed at any position beyond the focus ($F$), i.e., $u > f$.<br>If the object is placed between the pole ($P$) and the focus ($F$), the image formed is virtual, and it cannot be caught on a screen or used for the standard parallax alignment with a physical pin in front of the mirror.<br>Therefore, the object should be placed at any point beyond the focus ($F$) of the mirror to ensure a real image is formed.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (22 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":43124,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["$20 \\mathrm{~mm}$","$100 \\mathrm{~mm}$","$120 \\mathrm{~mm}$","$80 \\mathrm{~mm}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/HQ6I77Z0kD6IeFqgoOgG42mM0w1kX6tDGQtcnHid0zI.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\nTo obtain final image at infinity, object which is the image formed by objective should be at focal distance of eye-piece. By lens formula (for objective)\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& \\frac{1}{v_0}-\\frac{1}{u_0}=\\frac{1}{f_0} \\\\\n\\text { or, } \\quad & \\frac{1}{v_0}-\\frac{1}{-25}=\\frac{1}{20} \\\\\n\\Rightarrow \\quad & \\frac{1}{v_0}=\\frac{1}{20}-\\frac{1}{25}=\\frac{5-4}{100}=\\frac{1}{100} \\mathrm{~mm} \\\\\n\\therefore \\quad & v_0=100 \\mathrm{~mm}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\nTherefore the distance between the lenses\n$$\n=v_0+f_e=100 \\mathrm{~mm}+20 \\mathrm{~mm}=120 \\mathrm{~mm}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (12 May Online)","image":null},{"id":43122,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["Yes, it is possible with the same aperture size.","Possible also with an aperture half the present diameter.","No, it is not possible.","Given data is not sufficient."],"answer":0,"solution":"Given : $d=3 \\times 10^{-2} \\mathrm{~m}$\n$$\n\\lambda=5.5 \\times 10^{-7} \\mathrm{~m}\n$$\nLimit of resolution, $\\Delta \\theta=\\frac{1.22 \\lambda}{d}$\n$$\n=\\frac{1.22 \\times 5.5 \\times 10^{-7}}{3 \\times 10^{-2}}=2.23 \\times 10^{-5} \\mathrm{rad}\n$$\nAt a distance of $80 \\mathrm{~m}$, the telescope is able to resolve between two points which are separated by $2.23 \\times 10^{-5} \\times 80 \\mathrm{~m}$ $=1.78 \\times 10^{-3} \\mathrm{~m}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (26 May Online)","image":null},{"id":43103,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>0.4</mtext></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>0.2</mtext></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>0.9</mtext></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>0.8</mtext></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#956;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>:</mo></math> refractive index of rarer medium<br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#956;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>:</mo></math> retractive index of denser medium<br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>sin&#952;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#956;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#956;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>tan&#952;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#956;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#956;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac></math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mi>sin</mi><msub> <mi>&#952;</mi> <mi>C</mi> </msub> <mo>=</mo><mi>tan</mi><msub> <mi>&#952;</mi> <mi>B</mi> </msub> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mfrac> <mrow> <mi>sin</mi><msub> <mi>&#952;</mi> <mi>C</mi> </msub> </mrow> <mrow> <mi>sin</mi><msub> <mi>&#952;</mi> <mi>B</mi> </msub> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo><mfrac> <mrow> <mi>tan</mi><msub> <mi>&#952;</mi> <mi>B</mi> </msub> </mrow> <mrow> <mi>sin</mi><msub> <mi>&#952;</mi> <mi>B</mi> </msub> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo><mfrac> <mn>1</mn> <mrow> <mi>cos</mi><msub> <mi>&#952;</mi> <mi>B</mi> </msub> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo><mn>1.28</mn></mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mi>tan</mi><msub> <mi>&#952;</mi> <mi>B</mi> </msub> <mo>=</mo><mfrac> <mrow> <msub> <mi>&#956;</mi> <mn>1</mn> </msub> </mrow> <mrow> <msub> <mi>&#956;</mi> <mn>2</mn> </msub> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo><mfrac> <mrow> <msqrt> <mrow> <mn>1</mn><mo>&#8722;</mo><msup> <mrow> <mrow><mo>(</mo> <mrow> <mfrac> <mn>1</mn> <mrow> <mn>1.28</mn></mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> <mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow> <mn>2</mn> </msup> </mrow> </msqrt> </mrow> <mrow> <mrow><mo>(</mo> <mrow> <mfrac> <mn>1</mn> <mrow> <mn>1.28</mn></mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> <mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mo>=</mo><mn>0.8</mn></mrow> </math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (19 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":42994,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#952;</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>sin</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#952;</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msup><mi>sin</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#952;</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msup><mi>sin</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#952;</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><msup><mi>sin</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac></mfenced></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Given:<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>A</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>8</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>B</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>8</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p>For critical angle:<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sin</mi><mfenced><msub><mi>&#952;</mi><mi>c</mi></msub></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mi>A</mi></msub><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mi>B</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>c</mi><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>A</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>B</mi></msub><mi>c</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>8</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>8</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>&#952;</mi><mi>c</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>sin</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac></mfenced></math></p><p>Now for&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>T</mi><mi>I</mi><mi>R</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>&#952;</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>&#952;</mi><mi>C</mi></msub></math></p><p>So,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#952;</mi><mi>c</mi></msub><mo>&#62;</mo><msup><mi>sin</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac></mfenced></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jun Shift 2)","image":null}]